on&#8217;t just think of Help text, field descriptions, admin notices and pointers&#8230;all of which, Piklist makes super easy for you to implement. Forcing fields to be required and adding validation rules also provide the type of help a user needs to enter information correctly.</p>\n<p>During our past presentations at WordCampNYC in <a href="http://wordpress.tv/2012/09/04/steve-bruner-and-kevin-miller-building-powerful-websites-and-web-applications-with-piklist/">2012</a> and <a href="http://wordpress.tv/2014/11/16/kevin-miller-and-steve-bruner-customize-the-wordpress-admin-with-the-piklist-framework/">2014</a>, we focused on using Piklist to build really advanced websites with lots of Custom Post Types, Taxonomies, Settings and Custom Fields. This year we decided to do something different&#8230;use Piklist to make the &#8220;Add New Post&#8221; screen better for users.</p>\n<p>The session was recorded and once it&#8217;s made public we will let you know where you can watch it. Until then you can <a href="http://piklist.com/wcnyc">download the presentation plugin</a> and the <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/piklist/piklist-providing-inline-help-for-a-great-user-experience">slides</a>. Activate the plugin, and then add a new post. You should see some subtle, but important changes. This plugin shows off one of the most amazing Piklist features&#8230;the ability to change core WordPress fields. We call it &#8220;Extend&#8221;. Enjoy.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:60:"http://piklist.com/2015/11/03/wordcampnyc-presentation/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_l